values: I have another journal, if you're still terribly interested in my American life: Oh, the life of a band dork... That's where I'll (hopefully) update fairly often, especially if I know people are reading. Cheers!

I'm just updating to let y'all know that I'm still writing in this blog for a bit more time, and that I've made it safely back to the States (though most of you know this already).  I will update sometime later this week, but right now I'm adjusting and I'm having a bit of a rough time getting back into the swing of things.  It's also difficult to reminisce at the moment, so bear with me; I promise I'll post the comings and goings of my last week in England soon.  Thanks for understanding.

Scratch that; we're going to Dublin instead next weekend.  I kinda wanted to see Ireland more than Paris, anyway.

Any suggestions on what I should see?  Besides the Guinness factory, of course.  Apparently there's a Writer's Museum and a bunch of pubs (obviously).  Comments are appreciated! :)

I (honest to God) haven't thought much about what I want for Christmas besides being able to be home, decorate the tree, bake lots and lots of cookies, and see all of my friends and family again, but if you're at a loss at what to get me (if you're planning on getting me anything), here's what I can think of: + Gift cards for clothing stores. I am especially in desperate need of jeans; two of the three pairs I brought here are falling apart because of my fat butt, and I've been in need of new pants for a while, anyway. + Gift card for DSW. 'Nuff said. + This shirt in small size + This shirt in Ladies large + Possibly a new digital camera (as I think the lens opening in mine is SHOT), but I may take care of this myself + Novelty stockings! As in, tights. But not multicolored. Black or brown works for me. + Various apartment things (dishes, sheets, kitchen items, etc.) + Barnes and Noble gift cards + an mp3 player with a generous amount of memory And, as wishful thinking, a Wii. As always, I'm happy to receive anything, but I just figured I'd put this up for those of you who have NO idea what to get me. If you've already got me Bath & Body Works stuff, that's great and I'll definitely use it. If you haven't, don't; I'm still working on the stuff I've got from last year. Happy Holidays!

I woke up this morning at 6:30 with a sore throat. Not severe, but it felt uncomfortably familiar to about two weeks ago. I've gotta say, I'm absolutely sick of doctors and being ill, and of socialist medical care (or lack thereof). I don't even know if the antibiotics worked for my ear infection, because I still can't hear. If you can hear me God, I'm really pleading this time to get better. Umm on a happier note, the trip to Paris is still a go! Apparently we're planning to go the weekend after Thanksgiving (not the weekend of Black Friday, but the weekend after). I'll have the logistics and money issues down soon, for those of you whom this concerns. I still can't believe I have less than five weeks left of my trip; it seems like just yesterday (cliche, I'm well aware) that I was writing the first entry in this journal back at home, worrying about my trip and how I'd fare. But of course I'll discuss more of that when I get to the final entry of this journal (yes, this journal WILL have an end, but I still have my other journal that I'll try to update when I'm back in the States). Jumping around topics a bit...I was talking to a friend of mine, one of my flatmates, as we were having our late-night tea and biscuits (it's become a nightly thing for me), and we got into the topic of school systems and how they differed in the U.K. This topic actually comes up pretty often, as I have to explain exactly what age groups define "middle school" and "high school," and often an English person has to explain what their system is like to me. ANYWAY, they have this sort of school after their secondary school (the equivalent of grades 7-10, I think) that they call "college" or "prep school." I don't know if it's just for that sort of school or if the next thing I'll describe applies to all boarding schools, but they actually DO have "houses" for the students (and by "house" I mean like, for those of you who have any inkling of what goes on in Harry Potter, the different Houses, e.g. Gryffindor)! I always thought that was just a Harry Potter thing, but they really do have House competitions and sports and common rooms and whatnot. Maybe that's lame to you, but I thought it was really cool. It's LCR Beach Party night! And it's a beautiful 43 degrees outside, with a wind chill that makes it feel like 37. Did I mention it's also raining off and on? This is gonna be an interesting night...But we're making frozen cocktail drinks and throwing a beach party in the kitchen before we head to the LCR, so it should be fun. Guess we'll have to drink enough to withstand the freezing cold, haha. Anyway, I've got to start getting ready for that, but I figured I'd give you a post. Until next time... advert = advertisement So there are probably a billion words I've learned that I just can't remember off the top of my head. I'm afraid that when I come back to the States, I'm going to sound like the biggest retard ever. Oh well. Postcards were sent out yesterday to those of you who were expecting them!

I'm finally recovering from this awful illness. My throat doesn't hurt anymore and I haven't been coughing as much. My ear doesn't hurt, but it still has a horrid ringing and I can't hear much at all out of it, but I really hope that goes away. I don't want to be deaf in my right ear. I've been good and have been taking my antibiotics and using the ear drops (gives me an excuse to lie down and do nothing for 10 minutes). But I've been writing my philosophy paper (I FINALLY finished) and I'm going absolutely stir crazy in this room, in this flat. I can't stand being cooped up in here anymore. I'm getting depressed because I can't leave, and because I'm bored. Today I checked out two books for pleasure from the library, I'm so bored. And I'm quickly running out of money, which is bad. It means that I don't have money to travel. I might have enough to visit one more place for a weekend, unless I just budget travel with the International Student Society (they do a lot of day trips on weekends), which I might just do. It depends on how much they charge, as well. Like I said, those of you getting gifts from here are getting chocolate. I hope y'all like chocolate. I had this really weird dream last night (or this morning, I guess) that I was back in the states and there was this huge Christmas party with all of my friends and family. It was strange because instead of being really happy to be home, I was wanting to be back in England. And I had forgotten to buy everyone gifts, which was the point in the dream where I realized I was dreaming. I ended up partially waking up and trying to control another dream, but I've only been able to do that once in my life and it didn't work. Damn. Moral of the story is, it was weird that I was already missing England. I have a feeling that I'll miss it badly when I get back, probably about a few weeks after I return. Thank God for the internet, where we can talk to people internationally for free. Sorry for that rambling post, but I was bored and figured you guys wanted an update. My life isn't very interesting as I've been bedridden and ill and writing papers and watching movies, haha. Hopefully I'll have something more interesting in the future. Oh, by the way: if you think it's bad in the States that the sun's going down at 5:30, try being here, when the sun begins setting at 3:30. The sky is dark by 4:30 and it completely screws up your eating cycle.

Viral infection, with an ear infection. Picking up ear drops and amoxicillin tomorrow from the pharmacy, and requesting an extension for my essays and short story due this week. This so figures. Never have I ever had to request an extension or have an excuse to miss an exam, EVER, in the States. I thought I didn't get sick! UGH knocking on wood has obviously lost its effect.

A new series!  From the person that brought you the British to English Dictionary and "Things That Kinda Piss Me Off" comes Mind-Boggling Thoughts!

Nah, it's not really mind-boggling, but it does really make me wonder.  Here's the thing: they're really concerned about fire safety here.  Like, ridiculously concerned.  Let me outline some of our fire safety policies and the fire hazard rules:

1. Our doors shut automatically, and we're not allowed to prop them open, as it is a "fire hazard" to do so.
2. We are only allowed to have a certain amount of posters on the wall, e.g. the equivalent of half the floor space's worth.  It is a fire hazard to have any more than this.
3. If you purposely pull the fire alarm, you're automatically kicked out of the residence hall and fined 300 pounds (that's 600 American dollars, ouch).
4. If you misuse or set off the fire extinguishers, you're automatically kicked out of the residence hall and fined 300 pounds.
5. Basically, if you do anything against the fire code, you're kicked out of the residence halls and fined 300 pounds.  Period.

So yes, all is logical, except one thing: you're allowed to smoke in your room.  All of these fire safety rules, and all of these laws about not smoking in enclosed public venues, and you're allowed to smoke in your room.  Sure, you can't have too many papers on your walls, or open your door to let people know you're there, but you can light a stick on FIRE and smoke it.  It makes you wonder how well these smoke detectors work...

So anyway, that concludes this edition of "Mind-Boggling Thoughts." Tune in next time when I do something interesting.

chips = fries
biscuits = crunchy, pre-packaged cookies
cookies = chocolate chip, oatmeal, etc. (cookies you bake yourself)
squash = a kind of fruit juice concentrate (NOT a vegetable; people are astounded that we don't have this in the states)
aubergine = eggplant
crisps = chips (and I cannot CANNOT bring myself to call chips "crisps")
proper = very, really (but, as my RA says, this is a very "common" thing to say)
common = slangy, lower class
pound = TOO MUCH MONEY

Hope you enjoy this edition of Laura's British to American dictionary.  More to come when I learn more words.

One suitcase packed!  Two coats, 6 pairs of shoes, flip-flops, my winter shirts/sweaters, socks, hats, scarves, and gloves, and the hangers.  In the small suitcase.

You may now refer to me as Master [suitcase packer] :D

All right, so it's officially a week from today and I'm starting to get really anxious.  The book I have on studying abroad in the U.K. just freaks me out.  I hate the didactic voice it's written in.  It makes me anxious and I don't know why.  UGH.

I'll be fine.  It may take a while, but I know I'll make friends and have a lot of fun while I'm there, but right now I'm just really stressed out.

In other news, I put all of my music on my computer today, which took a LONG time.  Now I just have to get some of my dad's stuff and find some of my missing CDs (I have NO idea where they have gone, which means I'll probably have to clean my room before I leave to find anything).  I also downloaded Skype which, for those of you who don't know, is basically free internet phone.  So if you want to talk to me every once in a while and hear my wonderful voice (AKA something besides e-mail/this blog/AIM), you should download it too (after all, I'd probably like to hear your wonderful voice, as well).

Like I said, seven more days.  And three more days of work!

So I went to the bank a few days ago to "notify" them of my leaving the country, and they gave me their 1-800 number to call and do it officially. I call the number, and there was nothing in that stupid list of options that said anything about notifying them of an absence. First of all, I don't understand why they couldn't just put it into the computer at the bank. When I was THERE. IN PERSON. Second of all, screw automated phone message systems; I want to talk to a real person! I don't want them to freeze my account. I'm so mad about that. In other news, I got my travel guide, and dearest Jordan let me borrow a book that I can use as a diversion for my awful, awful plane ride. So now I have books, a Gameboy, and Nosha's sister's hard-as-hell cryptic crossword book (I'll figure it out eventually...). I still need to get + more hair ties (I seemed to have misplaced, umm, ALL OF THEM) + more hair clips (because they inevitably break) + probably more face wash + shampoo, floss, etc. + other things that I've definitely forgotten Four more workdays, and then I'm freeeeee :) 10 days left!

So I got a kickass colorful umbrella last night at about 11:15 or so from Wal-Mart (yes, it IS the fall of the American economy, but it's also one of the only places in Cary that's open past 9PM besides good ol' HT). Got my hair cut, too. I'm finally coming to the end of my working experience; today I received the penultimate schedule listing for me, and I'm pretty sure I know which days I work for my last "week" (AKA two days). I gotta say, working nearly full time as a cashier just reminds me every day of why I'm going to college (I've said it once and I'll say it many, many times). It does get somewhat easier to go to work since I'm going almost every day, kinda like a routine, but I'll sure as hell be glad when it's over and I'm really getting ready and buckled down for this trip. Christ, I can't believe I'm leaving in 16 days. I've still got a lot to do and read and take care of, but the list is definitely getting smaller.

Hello again!  Figured I'd put a few updates since it's been a few weeks since I last posted (and I should get used to posting in here, as I plan to update this journal a lot more often than I've been doing with my other journal).  I finally received my (tentative) class schedule last week, which is as follows:

+ Intro to Philosophy
+ 19th Century European Drama
+ Creative Writing: Drama

I also received my housing assignment; I get my own room!  How lovely.  I did so miss having my own room while at school (not that I didn't have kickass roommates ;).

In other news, I'm still working my ass off at the ol' HT, but it's bringing good money in and it's a fairly steady job, so I can't complain beyond the long hours and the customers.  I'm also starting to pull some stuff together, and I'm totally striking through the things I've done on the last list I posted.

So I guess that's it for now.  The countdown is at 19 days.  Gettin' there.
